Repositories — where packages come from.

Packages don't materialize out of thin air. They come from repositories: servers that host an HTTP-accessible catalog along with the package files themselves. Your distribution ships with a default set of repositories enabled, and you can add more.

On Debian and Ubuntu, repositories are configured in slash-etc-slash-apt-slash-sources-dot-list, and in dot-list files under sources-dot-list-dot-d. A typical line starts with the word deb, then a URL, then a codename, then a set of components. So: deb, the Ubuntu archive URL, then jammy, which is the codename of a specific Ubuntu release, then main, restricted, universe, multiverse. Those last four are the components, and they matter. main is officially-supported free software. restricted is proprietary drivers. universe is community-supported free software. And multiverse is proprietary software. So which components you enable decides what's even available to install.

On Red Hat and Fedora, repositories are configured as dot-repo files in slash-etc-slash-yum-dot-repos-dot-d, and each one is INI-style, with a baseurl, an enabled flag, a gpgcheck flag, and a gpgkey. You manage them with dnf config-manager, dash-dash-enable or dash-dash-disable, and you list them with dnf repolist.

Now, the most important security point in this whole section: GPG signatures gate trust. Packages from a real repository are cryptographically signed with that repository's GPG key, and your package manager verifies the signature before it installs anything. That's what protects you from a tampered package on a compromised mirror. So never, ever ignore a GPG error. Either install the key from a source you've verified, or don't install the package. This is exactly why adding a third-party repository, for Docker, say, always follows the same shape: add its GPG key, add the source, refresh the catalog, then install.

And one practical note for the Red Hat world: EPEL, which stands for Extra Packages for Enterprise Linux. The default RHEL repositories are deliberately conservative, so a lot of common tools simply aren't there. Running dnf install epel-release adds the EPEL repository, and suddenly packages like htop become available. On a fresh RHEL-family box, EPEL is almost a must-install. Ubuntu doesn't need an equivalent, because its universe repository already covers most of that ground. For the exam, know where repo config lives on each family, how to add a repo, and that GPG keys are what gate trust.
